# Python: Classes <a name="Classes" id="Classes"></a>

### Annotations <a name="Annotations" id="cdktf.Annotations"></a>

Includes API for attaching annotations such as warning messages to constructs.

#### Methods <a name="Methods" id="Methods"></a>

| **Name**                                                             | **Description**                                                    |
| -------------------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------ |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Annotations.addError">add_error</a></code>     | Adds an { "error": < message > } metadata entry to this construct. |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Annotations.addInfo">add_info</a></code>       | Adds an info metadata entry to this construct.                     |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Annotations.addWarning">add_warning</a></code> | Adds a warning metadata entry to this construct.                   |

---

##### `add_error` <a name="add_error" id="cdktf.Annotations.addError"></a>

```python
def add_error(
  message: str
) - > None
```

Adds an { "error": < message > } metadata entry to this construct.

The toolkit will fail synthesis when errors are reported.

###### `message`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="message" id="cdktf.Annotations.addError.parameter.message"></a>

- _Type:_ str

The error message.

---

##### `add_info` <a name="add_info" id="cdktf.Annotations.addInfo"></a>

```python
def add_info(
  message: str
) - > None
```

Adds an info metadata entry to this construct.

The CLI will display the info message when apps are synthesized.

###### `message`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="message" id="cdktf.Annotations.addInfo.parameter.message"></a>

- _Type:_ str

The info message.

---

##### `add_warning` <a name="add_warning" id="cdktf.Annotations.addWarning"></a>

```python
def add_warning(
  message: str
) - > None
```

Adds a warning metadata entry to this construct.

The CLI will display the warning when an app is synthesized.
In a future release the CLI might introduce a --strict flag which
will then fail the synthesis if it encounters a warning.

###### `message`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="message" id="cdktf.Annotations.addWarning.parameter.message"></a>

- _Type:_ str

The warning message.

---

#### Static Functions <a name="Static Functions" id="Static Functions"></a>

| **Name**                                            | **Description**                                    |
| --------------------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------- |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Annotations.of">of</a></code> | Returns the annotations API for a construct scope. |

---

##### `of` <a name="of" id="cdktf.Annotations.of"></a>

```python
import cdktf

cdktf.Annotations.of(
  scope: IConstruct
)
```

Returns the annotations API for a construct scope.

###### `scope`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="scope" id="cdktf.Annotations.of.parameter.scope"></a>

- _Type:_ constructs.IConstruct

The scope.

```python
def dynamic(
  attributes: typing.Mapping[typing.Any]
) - > IResolvable
```

##### `for_expression_for_list` <a name="for_expression_for_list" id="cdktf.DynamicListTerraformIterator.forExpressionForList"></a>

```python
def for_expression_for_list(
  expression: typing.Union[str, IResolvable]
) - > IResolvable
```

Creates a for expression that results in a list.

This method allows you to create every possible for expression, but requires more knowledge about
Terraform's for expression syntax.
For the most common use cases you can use keys(), values(), and pluckProperty() instead.

You may write any valid Terraform for each expression, e.g.
`TerraformIterator.fromList(myIteratorSourceVar).forExpressionForList("val.foo if val.bar == true")`
will result in `[ for key, val in var.myIteratorSource: val.foo if val.bar == true ]`.

As this returns an IResolvable you might need to wrap the output in
a Token, e.g. `Token.asString`.

###### `expression`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="expression" id="cdktf.DynamicListTerraformIterator.forExpressionForList.parameter.expression"></a>

- _Type:_ typing.Union[str, <a href="#cdktf.IResolvable">IResolvable</a>]

The expression to use in the for mapping.

---

##### `for_expression_for_map` <a name="for_expression_for_map" id="cdktf.DynamicListTerraformIterator.forExpressionForMap"></a>

```python
def for_expression_for_map(
  key_expression: typing.Union[str, IResolvable],
  value_expression: typing.Union[str, IResolvable]
) - > IResolvable
```

Creates a for expression that results in a map.

This method allows you to create every possible for expression, but requires more knowledge about
Terraforms for expression syntax.
For the most common use cases you can use keys(), values(), and pluckProperty instead.

You may write any valid Terraform for each expression, e.g.
`TerraformIterator.fromMap(myIteratorSourceVar).forExpressionForMap("key", "val.foo if val.bar == true")`
will result in `{ for key, val in var.myIteratorSource: key = > val.foo if val.bar == true }`.

As this returns an IResolvable you might need to wrap the output in
a Token, e.g. `Token.asString`.

###### `key_expression`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="key_expression" id="cdktf.DynamicListTerraformIterator.forExpressionForMap.parameter.keyExpression"></a>

- _Type:_ typing.Union[str, <a href="#cdktf.IResolvable">IResolvable</a>]

The expression to use as key in the for mapping.

---

###### `value_expression`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="value_expression" id="cdktf.DynamicListTerraformIterator.forExpressionForMap.parameter.valueExpression"></a>

- _Type:_ typing.Union[str, <a href="#cdktf.IResolvable">IResolvable</a>]

The expression to use as value in the for mapping.

##### `from_complex_list` <a name="from_complex_list" id="cdktf.DynamicListTerraformIterator.fromComplexList"></a>

```python
import cdktf

cdktf.DynamicListTerraformIterator.from_complex_list(
  list: typing.Union[IResolvable, ComplexList, StringMapList, NumberMapList, BooleanMapList, AnyMapList],
  map_key_attribute_name: str
)
```

Creates a new iterator from a complex list.

One example for this would be a list of maps.
The list will be converted into a map with the mapKeyAttributeName as the key.

_Example_

```python
# Example automatically generated from non-compiling source. May contain errors.
cert = AcmCertificate(self, "cert",
    domain_name="example.com",
    validation_method="DNS"
)

dvo_iterator = TerraformIterator.from_complex_list(cert.domain_validation_options, "domain_name")

Route53Record(self, "record",
    allow_overwrite=True,
    name=dvo_iterator.get_string("name"),
    records=[dvo_iterator.get_string("record")],
    ttl=60,
    type=dvo_iterator.get_string("type"),
    zone_id=Token.as_string(data_aws_route53_zone_example.zone_id),
    for_each=dvo_iterator
)
```

##### `abs` <a name="abs" id="cdktf.Fn.abs"></a>

```python
import cdktf

cdktf.Fn.abs(
  num: typing.Union[int, float]
)
```

{@link https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/functions/abs abs} returns the absolute value of the given number. In other words, if the number is zero or positive then it is returned as-is, but if it is negative then it is multiplied by -1 to make it positive before returning it.

###### `num`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="num" id="cdktf.Fn.abs.parameter.num"></a>

- _Type:_ typing.Union[int, float]

The {@link https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/functions/setintersection setintersection} function takes multiple sets and produces a single set containing only the elements that all of the given sets have in common. In other words, it computes the [intersection](<https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Intersection_(set_theory)>) of the sets.

##### `lookup_nested` <a name="lookup_nested" id="cdktf.Fn.lookupNested"></a>

```python
import cdktf

  input_map: typing.Any,
  path: typing.List[typing.Any]
)
```

returns a property access expression that accesses the property at the given path in the given inputMap.

For example lookupNested(x, ["a", "b", "c"]) will return a Terraform expression like x["a"]["b"]["c"]

##### `abs` <a name="abs" id="cdktf.FnGenerated.abs"></a>

```python
import cdktf

cdktf.FnGenerated.abs(
  num: typing.Union[int, float]
)
```

{@link https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/functions/abs abs} returns the absolute value of the given number. In other words, if the number is zero or positive then it is returned as-is, but if it is negative then it is multiplied by -1 to make it positive before returning it.

###### `num`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="num" id="cdktf.FnGenerated.abs.parameter.num"></a>

- _Type:_ typing.Union[int, float]

The {@link https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/functions/setsubtract setsubtract} function returns a new set containing the elements from the first set that are not present in the second set. In other words, it computes the [relative complement](<https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complement_(set_theory)#Relative_complement>) of the second set.

###### `a`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="a" id="cdktf.FnGenerated.setsubtract.parameter.a"></a>

- _Type:_ typing.List[typing.Any]

---

###### `b`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="b" id="cdktf.FnGenerated.setsubtract.parameter.b"></a>

- _Type:_ typing.List[typing.Any]

---

### Lazy <a name="Lazy" id="cdktf.Lazy"></a>

Lazily produce a value.

Can be used to return a string, list or numeric value whose actual value
will only be calculated later, during synthesis.

#### Initializers <a name="Initializers" id="cdktf.Lazy.Initializer"></a>

```python
import cdktf

cdktf.Lazy()
```

| **Name** | **Type** | **Description** |
| -------- | -------- | --------------- |

---

#### Static Functions <a name="Static Functions" id="Static Functions"></a>

| **Name**                                                        | **Description**                               |
| --------------------------------------------------------------- | --------------------------------------------- |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Lazy.anyValue">any_value</a></code>       | Produces a lazy token from an untyped value.  |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Lazy.listValue">list_value</a></code>     | Returns a list-ified token for a lazy value.  |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Lazy.numberValue">number_value</a></code> | Returns a numberified token for a lazy value. |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Lazy.stringValue">string_value</a></code> | Returns a stringified token for a lazy value. |

---

##### `any_value` <a name="any_value" id="cdktf.Lazy.anyValue"></a>

```python
import cdktf

cdktf.Lazy.any_value(
  producer: IAnyProducer,
  display_hint: str = None,
  omit_empty_array: bool = None
)
```

Produces a lazy token from an untyped value.

###### `producer`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="producer" id="cdktf.Lazy.anyValue.parameter.producer"></a>

- _Type:_ <a href="#cdktf.IAnyProducer">IAnyProducer</a>

The lazy producer.

---

##### `for_expression_for_list` <a name="for_expression_for_list" id="cdktf.ListTerraformIterator.forExpressionForList"></a>

```python
def for_expression_for_list(
  expression: typing.Union[str, IResolvable]
) - > IResolvable
```

Creates a for expression that results in a list.

This method allows you to create every possible for expression, but requires more knowledge about
Terraform's for expression syntax.
For the most common use cases you can use keys(), values(), and pluckProperty() instead.

You may write any valid Terraform for each expression, e.g.
`TerraformIterator.fromList(myIteratorSourceVar).forExpressionForList("val.foo if val.bar == true")`
will result in `[ for key, val in var.myIteratorSource: val.foo if val.bar == true ]`.

As this returns an IResolvable you might need to wrap the output in
a Token, e.g. `Token.asString`.

###### `expression`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="expression" id="cdktf.ListTerraformIterator.forExpressionForList.parameter.expression"></a>

- _Type:_ typing.Union[str, <a href="#cdktf.IResolvable">IResolvable</a>]

The expression to use in the for mapping.

---

##### `for_expression_for_map` <a name="for_expression_for_map" id="cdktf.ListTerraformIterator.forExpressionForMap"></a>

```python
def for_expression_for_map(
  key_expression: typing.Union[str, IResolvable],
  value_expression: typing.Union[str, IResolvable]
) - > IResolvable
```

Creates a for expression that results in a map.

This method allows you to create every possible for expression, but requires more knowledge about
Terraforms for expression syntax.
For the most common use cases you can use keys(), values(), and pluckProperty instead.

You may write any valid Terraform for each expression, e.g.
`TerraformIterator.fromMap(myIteratorSourceVar).forExpressionForMap("key", "val.foo if val.bar == true")`
will result in `{ for key, val in var.myIteratorSource: key = > val.foo if val.bar == true }`.

As this returns an IResolvable you might need to wrap the output in
a Token, e.g. `Token.asString`.

###### `key_expression`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="key_expression" id="cdktf.ListTerraformIterator.forExpressionForMap.parameter.keyExpression"></a>

- _Type:_ typing.Union[str, <a href="#cdktf.IResolvable">IResolvable</a>]

The expression to use as key in the for mapping.

---

###### `value_expression`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="value_expression" id="cdktf.ListTerraformIterator.forExpressionForMap.parameter.valueExpression"></a>

- _Type:_ typing.Union[str, <a href="#cdktf.IResolvable">IResolvable</a>]

The expression to use as value in the for mapping.

##### `from_complex_list` <a name="from_complex_list" id="cdktf.ListTerraformIterator.fromComplexList"></a>

```python
import cdktf

cdktf.ListTerraformIterator.from_complex_list(
  list: typing.Union[IResolvable, ComplexList, StringMapList, NumberMapList, BooleanMapList, AnyMapList],
  map_key_attribute_name: str
)
```

Creates a new iterator from a complex list.

One example for this would be a list of maps.
The list will be converted into a map with the mapKeyAttributeName as the key.

_Example_

```python
# Example automatically generated from non-compiling source. May contain errors.
cert = AcmCertificate(self, "cert",
    domain_name="example.com",
    validation_method="DNS"
)

dvo_iterator = TerraformIterator.from_complex_list(cert.domain_validation_options, "domain_name")

Route53Record(self, "record",
    allow_overwrite=True,
    name=dvo_iterator.get_string("name"),
    records=[dvo_iterator.get_string("record")],
    ttl=60,
    type=dvo_iterator.get_string("type"),
    zone_id=Token.as_string(data_aws_route53_zone_example.zone_id),
    for_each=dvo_iterator
)
```

###### `list`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="list" id="cdktf.ListTerraformIterator.fromComplexList.parameter.list"></a>

- _Type:_ typing.Union[<a href="#cdktf.IResolvable">IResolvable</a>, <a href="#cdktf.ComplexList">ComplexList</a>, <a href="#cdktf.StringMapList">StringMapList</a>, <a href="#cdktf.NumberMapList">NumberMapList</a>, <a href="#cdktf.BooleanMapList">BooleanMapList</a>, <a href="#cdktf.AnyMapList">AnyMapList</a>]

the list to iterate over.

---

###### `map_key_attribute_name`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="map_key_attribute_name" id="cdktf.ListTerraformIterator.fromComplexList.parameter.mapKeyAttributeName"></a>

- _Type:_ str

the name of the attribute that should be used as the key in the map.

Visit https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cdktf/concepts/iterators#using-iterators-on-complex-lists for more information.

---

### Manifest <a name="Manifest" id="cdktf.Manifest"></a>

##### `for_expression_for_list` <a name="for_expression_for_list" id="cdktf.MapTerraformIterator.forExpressionForList"></a>

```python
def for_expression_for_list(
  expression: typing.Union[str, IResolvable]
) - > IResolvable
```

Creates a for expression that results in a list.

This method allows you to create every possible for expression, but requires more knowledge about
Terraform's for expression syntax.
For the most common use cases you can use keys(), values(), and pluckProperty() instead.

You may write any valid Terraform for each expression, e.g.
`TerraformIterator.fromList(myIteratorSourceVar).forExpressionForList("val.foo if val.bar == true")`
will result in `[ for key, val in var.myIteratorSource: val.foo if val.bar == true ]`.

As this returns an IResolvable you might need to wrap the output in
a Token, e.g. `Token.asString`.

###### `expression`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="expression" id="cdktf.MapTerraformIterator.forExpressionForList.parameter.expression"></a>

- _Type:_ typing.Union[str, <a href="#cdktf.IResolvable">IResolvable</a>]

The expression to use in the for mapping.

---

##### `for_expression_for_map` <a name="for_expression_for_map" id="cdktf.MapTerraformIterator.forExpressionForMap"></a>

```python
def for_expression_for_map(
  key_expression: typing.Union[str, IResolvable],
  value_expression: typing.Union[str, IResolvable]
) - > IResolvable
```

Creates a for expression that results in a map.

This method allows you to create every possible for expression, but requires more knowledge about
Terraforms for expression syntax.
For the most common use cases you can use keys(), values(), and pluckProperty instead.

You may write any valid Terraform for each expression, e.g.
`TerraformIterator.fromMap(myIteratorSourceVar).forExpressionForMap("key", "val.foo if val.bar == true")`
will result in `{ for key, val in var.myIteratorSource: key = > val.foo if val.bar == true }`.

As this returns an IResolvable you might need to wrap the output in
a Token, e.g. `Token.asString`.

###### `key_expression`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="key_expression" id="cdktf.MapTerraformIterator.forExpressionForMap.parameter.keyExpression"></a>

- _Type:_ typing.Union[str, <a href="#cdktf.IResolvable">IResolvable</a>]

The expression to use as key in the for mapping.

---

###### `value_expression`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="value_expression" id="cdktf.MapTerraformIterator.forExpressionForMap.parameter.valueExpression"></a>

- _Type:_ typing.Union[str, <a href="#cdktf.IResolvable">IResolvable</a>]

The expression to use as value in the for mapping.

##### `from_complex_list` <a name="from_complex_list" id="cdktf.MapTerraformIterator.fromComplexList"></a>

```python
import cdktf

cdktf.MapTerraformIterator.from_complex_list(
  list: typing.Union[IResolvable, ComplexList, StringMapList, NumberMapList, BooleanMapList, AnyMapList],
  map_key_attribute_name: str
)
```

Creates a new iterator from a complex list.

One example for this would be a list of maps.
The list will be converted into a map with the mapKeyAttributeName as the key.

_Example_

```python
# Example automatically generated from non-compiling source. May contain errors.
cert = AcmCertificate(self, "cert",
    domain_name="example.com",
    validation_method="DNS"
)

dvo_iterator = TerraformIterator.from_complex_list(cert.domain_validation_options, "domain_name")

Route53Record(self, "record",
    allow_overwrite=True,
    name=dvo_iterator.get_string("name"),
    records=[dvo_iterator.get_string("record")],
    ttl=60,
    type=dvo_iterator.get_string("type"),
    zone_id=Token.as_string(data_aws_route53_zone_example.zone_id),
    for_each=dvo_iterator
)
```

### NamedCloudWorkspace <a name="NamedCloudWorkspace" id="cdktf.NamedCloudWorkspace"></a>

The name of a single Terraform Cloud workspace.

You will only be able to use the workspace specified in the configuration with this working directory, and cannot manage workspaces from the CLI (e.g. terraform workspace select or terraform workspace new).

### Op <a name="Op" id="cdktf.Op"></a>

This class contains static functions for all arithmetical and logical operators in the Terraform configuration language.

#### Initializers <a name="Initializers" id="cdktf.Op.Initializer"></a>

```python

```

| **Name** | **Type** | **Description** |
| -------- | -------- | --------------- |

---

#### Static Functions <a name="Static Functions" id="Static Functions"></a>

| **Name**                                           | **Description**          |
| -------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------ |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Op.add">add</a></code>       | Renders left + right.    |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Op.and">and</a></code>       | Renders left && right.   |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Op.div">div</a></code>       | Renders left / right.    |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Op.eq">eq</a></code>         | Renders left == right.   |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Op.gt">gt</a></code>         | Renders left > right.    |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Op.gte">gte</a></code>       | Renders left >= right.   |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Op.lt">lt</a></code>         | Renders left < right.    |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Op.lte">lte</a></code>       | Renders left < = right.  |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Op.mod">mod</a></code>       | Renders left % right.    |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Op.mul">mul</a></code>       | Renders left \* right.   |

##### `dynamic` <a name="dynamic" id="cdktf.ResourceTerraformIterator.dynamic"></a>

```python
def dynamic(
  attributes: typing.Mapping[typing.Any]
) - > IResolvable
```

Creates a dynamic expression that can be used to loop over this iterator in a dynamic block.

As this returns an IResolvable you might need to wrap the output in
a Token, e.g. `Token.asString`.
See https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cdktf/concepts/iterators#using-iterators-for-list-attributes

###### `attributes`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="attributes" id="cdktf.ResourceTerraformIterator.dynamic.parameter.attributes"></a>

- _Type:_ typing.Mapping[typing.Any]

---

##### `for_expression_for_list` <a name="for_expression_for_list" id="cdktf.ResourceTerraformIterator.forExpressionForList"></a>

```python
def for_expression_for_list(
  expression: typing.Union[str, IResolvable]
) - > IResolvable
```

Creates a for expression that results in a list.

This method allows you to create every possible for expression, but requires more knowledge about
Terraform's for expression syntax.
For the most common use cases you can use keys(), values(), and pluckProperty() instead.

You may write any valid Terraform for each expression, e.g.
`TerraformIterator.fromList(myIteratorSourceVar).forExpressionForList("val.foo if val.bar == true")`
will result in `[ for key, val in var.myIteratorSource: val.foo if val.bar == true ]`.

As this returns an IResolvable you might need to wrap the output in
a Token, e.g. `Token.asString`.

###### `expression`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="expression" id="cdktf.ResourceTerraformIterator.forExpressionForList.parameter.expression"></a>

- _Type:_ typing.Union[str, <a href="#cdktf.IResolvable">IResolvable</a>]

The expression to use in the for mapping.

---

##### `for_expression_for_map` <a name="for_expression_for_map" id="cdktf.ResourceTerraformIterator.forExpressionForMap"></a>

```python
def for_expression_for_map(
  key_expression: typing.Union[str, IResolvable],
  value_expression: typing.Union[str, IResolvable]
) - > IResolvable
```

Creates a for expression that results in a map.

This method allows you to create every possible for expression, but requires more knowledge about
Terraforms for expression syntax.
For the most common use cases you can use keys(), values(), and pluckProperty instead.

You may write any valid Terraform for each expression, e.g.
`TerraformIterator.fromMap(myIteratorSourceVar).forExpressionForMap("key", "val.foo if val.bar == true")`
will result in `{ for key, val in var.myIteratorSource: key = > val.foo if val.bar == true }`.

As this returns an IResolvable you might need to wrap the output in
a Token, e.g. `Token.asString`.

###### `key_expression`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="key_expression" id="cdktf.ResourceTerraformIterator.forExpressionForMap.parameter.keyExpression"></a>

- _Type:_ typing.Union[str, <a href="#cdktf.IResolvable">IResolvable</a>]

The expression to use as key in the for mapping.

---

###### `value_expression`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="value_expression" id="cdktf.ResourceTerraformIterator.forExpressionForMap.parameter.valueExpression"></a>

- _Type:_ typing.Union[str, <a href="#cdktf.IResolvable">IResolvable</a>]

The expression to use as value in the for mapping.

##### `keys` <a name="keys" id="cdktf.ResourceTerraformIterator.keys"></a>

```python
def keys() - > IResolvable
```

Creates a for expression that maps the iterators to its keys.

For lists these would be the indices, for maps the keys.
As this returns an IResolvable you might need to wrap the output in
a Token, e.g. `Token.asString`.

##### `pluck_property` <a name="pluck_property" id="cdktf.ResourceTerraformIterator.pluckProperty"></a>

```python
def pluck_property(
  property: str
) - > IResolvable
```

Creates a for expression that accesses the key on each element of the iterator.

As this returns an IResolvable you might need to wrap the output in
a Token, e.g. `Token.asString`.

###### `property`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="property" id="cdktf.ResourceTerraformIterator.pluckProperty.parameter.property"></a>

- _Type:_ str

The property of the iterators values to map to.

---

##### `values` <a name="values" id="cdktf.ResourceTerraformIterator.values"></a>

```python
def values() - > IResolvable
```

Creates a for expression that maps the iterators to its value in case it is a map.

For lists these would stay the same.
As this returns an IResolvable you might need to wrap the output in
a Token, e.g. `Token.asString`.

##### `from_complex_list` <a name="from_complex_list" id="cdktf.ResourceTerraformIterator.fromComplexList"></a>

```python
import cdktf

cdktf.ResourceTerraformIterator.from_complex_list(
  list: typing.Union[IResolvable, ComplexList, StringMapList, NumberMapList, BooleanMapList, AnyMapList],
  map_key_attribute_name: str
)
```

Creates a new iterator from a complex list.

One example for this would be a list of maps.
The list will be converted into a map with the mapKeyAttributeName as the key.

_Example_

```python
# Example automatically generated from non-compiling source. May contain errors.
cert = AcmCertificate(self, "cert",
    domain_name="example.com",
    validation_method="DNS"
)

dvo_iterator = TerraformIterator.from_complex_list(cert.domain_validation_options, "domain_name")

Route53Record(self, "record",
    allow_overwrite=True,
    name=dvo_iterator.get_string("name"),
    records=[dvo_iterator.get_string("record")],
    ttl=60,
    type=dvo_iterator.get_string("type"),
    zone_id=Token.as_string(data_aws_route53_zone_example.zone_id),
    for_each=dvo_iterator
)
```

###### `list`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="list" id="cdktf.ResourceTerraformIterator.fromComplexList.parameter.list"></a>

- _Type:_ typing.Union[<a href="#cdktf.IResolvable">IResolvable</a>, <a href="#cdktf.ComplexList">ComplexList</a>, <a href="#cdktf.StringMapList">StringMapList</a>, <a href="#cdktf.NumberMapList">NumberMapList</a>, <a href="#cdktf.BooleanMapList">BooleanMapList</a>, <a href="#cdktf.AnyMapList">AnyMapList</a>]

the list to iterate over.

---

###### `map_key_attribute_name`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="map_key_attribute_name" id="cdktf.ResourceTerraformIterator.fromComplexList.parameter.mapKeyAttributeName"></a>

- _Type:_ str

the name of the attribute that should be used as the key in the map.

Visit https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cdktf/concepts/iterators#using-iterators-on-complex-lists for more information.

---

### TaggedCloudWorkspaces <a name="TaggedCloudWorkspaces" id="cdktf.TaggedCloudWorkspaces"></a>

A set of Terraform Cloud workspace tags.

You will be able to use this working directory with any workspaces that have all of the specified tags, and can use the terraform workspace commands to switch between them or create new workspaces. New workspaces will automatically have the specified tags. This option conflicts with name.

##### `dynamic` <a name="dynamic" id="cdktf.TerraformIterator.dynamic"></a>

```python
def dynamic(
  attributes: typing.Mapping[typing.Any]
) - > IResolvable
```

Creates a dynamic expression that can be used to loop over this iterator in a dynamic block.

As this returns an IResolvable you might need to wrap the output in
a Token, e.g. `Token.asString`.
See https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cdktf/concepts/iterators#using-iterators-for-list-attributes

##### `for_expression_for_list` <a name="for_expression_for_list" id="cdktf.TerraformIterator.forExpressionForList"></a>

```python
def for_expression_for_list(
  expression: typing.Union[str, IResolvable]
) - > IResolvable
```

Creates a for expression that results in a list.

This method allows you to create every possible for expression, but requires more knowledge about
Terraform's for expression syntax.
For the most common use cases you can use keys(), values(), and pluckProperty() instead.

You may write any valid Terraform for each expression, e.g.
`TerraformIterator.fromList(myIteratorSourceVar).forExpressionForList("val.foo if val.bar == true")`
will result in `[ for key, val in var.myIteratorSource: val.foo if val.bar == true ]`.

As this returns an IResolvable you might need to wrap the output in
a Token, e.g. `Token.asString`.

###### `expression`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="expression" id="cdktf.TerraformIterator.forExpressionForList.parameter.expression"></a>

- _Type:_ typing.Union[str, <a href="#cdktf.IResolvable">IResolvable</a>]

The expression to use in the for mapping.

---

##### `for_expression_for_map` <a name="for_expression_for_map" id="cdktf.TerraformIterator.forExpressionForMap"></a>

```python
def for_expression_for_map(
  key_expression: typing.Union[str, IResolvable],
  value_expression: typing.Union[str, IResolvable]
) - > IResolvable
```

Creates a for expression that results in a map.

This method allows you to create every possible for expression, but requires more knowledge about
Terraforms for expression syntax.
For the most common use cases you can use keys(), values(), and pluckProperty instead.

You may write any valid Terraform for each expression, e.g.
`TerraformIterator.fromMap(myIteratorSourceVar).forExpressionForMap("key", "val.foo if val.bar == true")`
will result in `{ for key, val in var.myIteratorSource: key = > val.foo if val.bar == true }`.

As this returns an IResolvable you might need to wrap the output in
a Token, e.g. `Token.asString`.

###### `key_expression`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="key_expression" id="cdktf.TerraformIterator.forExpressionForMap.parameter.keyExpression"></a>

- _Type:_ typing.Union[str, <a href="#cdktf.IResolvable">IResolvable</a>]

The expression to use as key in the for mapping.

---

###### `value_expression`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="value_expression" id="cdktf.TerraformIterator.forExpressionForMap.parameter.valueExpression"></a>

- _Type:_ typing.Union[str, <a href="#cdktf.IResolvable">IResolvable</a>]

The expression to use as value in the for mapping.

##### `from_complex_list` <a name="from_complex_list" id="cdktf.TerraformIterator.fromComplexList"></a>

```python
import cdktf

cdktf.TerraformIterator.from_complex_list(
  list: typing.Union[IResolvable, ComplexList, StringMapList, NumberMapList, BooleanMapList, AnyMapList],
  map_key_attribute_name: str
)
```

Creates a new iterator from a complex list.

One example for this would be a list of maps.
The list will be converted into a map with the mapKeyAttributeName as the key.

_Example_

```python
# Example automatically generated from non-compiling source. May contain errors.
cert = AcmCertificate(self, "cert",
    domain_name="example.com",
    validation_method="DNS"
)

dvo_iterator = TerraformIterator.from_complex_list(cert.domain_validation_options, "domain_name")

Route53Record(self, "record",
    allow_overwrite=True,
    name=dvo_iterator.get_string("name"),
    records=[dvo_iterator.get_string("record")],
    ttl=60,
    type=dvo_iterator.get_string("type"),
    zone_id=Token.as_string(data_aws_route53_zone_example.zone_id),
    for_each=dvo_iterator
)
```

###### `list`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="list" id="cdktf.TerraformIterator.fromComplexList.parameter.list"></a>

- _Type:_ typing.Union[<a href="#cdktf.IResolvable">IResolvable</a>, <a href="#cdktf.ComplexList">ComplexList</a>, <a href="#cdktf.StringMapList">StringMapList</a>, <a href="#cdktf.NumberMapList">NumberMapList</a>, <a href="#cdktf.BooleanMapList">BooleanMapList</a>, <a href="#cdktf.AnyMapList">AnyMapList</a>]

the list to iterate over.

---

###### `map_key_attribute_name`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="map_key_attribute_name" id="cdktf.TerraformIterator.fromComplexList.parameter.mapKeyAttributeName"></a>

- _Type:_ str

the name of the attribute that should be used as the key in the map.

Visit https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cdktf/concepts/iterators#using-iterators-on-complex-lists for more information.

---

### TerraformResourceTargets <a name="TerraformResourceTargets" id="cdktf.TerraformResourceTargets"></a>

### TerraformSelf <a name="TerraformSelf" id="cdktf.TerraformSelf"></a>

Expressions in connection blocks cannot refer to their parent resource by name.

References create dependencies, and referring to a resource by name within its own block would create a dependency cycle.
Instead, expressions can use the self object, which represents the connection's parent resource and has all of that resource's attributes.
For example, use self.public_ip to reference an aws_instance's public_ip attribute.

#### Initializers <a name="Initializers" id="cdktf.TerraformSelf.Initializer"></a>

```python
import cdktf

cdktf.TerraformSelf()
```

| **Name** | **Type** | **Description** |
| -------- | -------- | --------------- |

---

#### Static Functions <a name="Static Functions" id="Static Functions"></a>

| **Name**                                                             | **Description**                                                                     |
| -------------------------------------------------------------------- | ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.TerraformSelf.getAny">get_any</a></code>       | Only usable within a connection block to reference the connections parent resource. |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.TerraformSelf.getNumber">get_number</a></code> | Only usable within a connection block to reference the connections parent resource. |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.TerraformSelf.getString">get_string</a></code> | Only usable within a connection block to reference the connections parent resource. |

---

##### `get_any` <a name="get_any" id="cdktf.TerraformSelf.getAny"></a>

```python
import cdktf

cdktf.TerraformSelf.get_any(
  key: str
)
```

Only usable within a connection block to reference the connections parent resource.

Access a property on the resource like this: `getAny("hostPort")`

###### `key`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="key" id="cdktf.TerraformSelf.getAny.parameter.key"></a>

- _Type:_ str

---

```python
  key: str
```

### Token <a name="Token" id="cdktf.Token"></a>

Represents a special or lazily-evaluated value.

Can be used to delay evaluation of a certain value in case, for example,
that it requires some context or late-bound data. Can also be used to
mark values that need special processing at document rendering time.

Tokens can be embedded into strings while retaining their original
semantics.

#### Initializers <a name="Initializers" id="cdktf.Token.Initializer"></a>

```python
import cdktf

cdktf.Token()
```

| **Name** | **Type** | **Description** |
| -------- | -------- | --------------- |

---

#### Static Functions <a name="Static Functions" id="Static Functions"></a>

| **Name**                                                            | **Description**                                          |
| ------------------------------------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------- |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Token.asAny">as_any</a></code>                | Return a resolvable representation of the given value.   |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Token.asAnyMap">as_any_map</a></code>         | Return a reversible map representation of this token.    |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Token.asBooleanMap">as_boolean_map</a></code> | Return a reversible map representation of this token.    |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Token.asList">as_list</a></code>              | Return a reversible list representation of this token.   |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Token.asMap">as_map</a></code>                | Return a reversible map representation of this token.    |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Token.asNumber">as_number</a></code>          | Return a reversible number representation of this token. |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Token.asNumberList">as_number_list</a></code> | Return a reversible list representation of this token.   |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Token.asNumberMap">as_number_map</a></code>   | Return a reversible map representation of this token.    |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Token.asString">as_string</a></code>          | Return a reversible string representation of this token. |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Token.asStringMap">as_string_map</a></code>   | Return a reversible map representation of this token.    |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Token.isUnresolved">is_unresolved</a></code>  | Returns true if obj represents an unresolved value.      |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Token.nullValue">null_value</a></code>        | Return a Token containing a `null` value.                |

##### `as_string` <a name="as_string" id="cdktf.Token.asString"></a>

```python
import cdktf

cdktf.Token.as_string(
  value: typing.Any,
  display_hint: str = None
)
```

Return a reversible string representation of this token.

If the Token is initialized with a literal, the stringified value of the
literal is returned. Otherwise, a special quoted string representation
of the Token is returned that can be embedded into other strings.

Strings with quoted Tokens in them can be restored back into
complex values with the Tokens restored by calling `resolve()`
on the string.

###### `value`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="value" id="cdktf.Token.asString.parameter.value"></a>

- _Type:_ typing.Any

---

###### `display_hint`<sup>Optional</sup> <a name="display_hint" id="cdktf.Token.asString.parameter.displayHint"></a>

- _Type:_ str
- _Default:_ no display hint

A hint for the Token's purpose when stringifying it.

---

##### `as_string_map` <a name="as_string_map" id="cdktf.Token.asStringMap"></a>

```python
import cdktf

cdktf.Token.as_string_map(
  value: typing.Any,
  display_hint: str = None
)
```

Return a reversible map representation of this token.

###### `value`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="value" id="cdktf.Token.asStringMap.parameter.value"></a>

- _Type:_ typing.Any

---

###### `display_hint`<sup>Optional</sup> <a name="display_hint" id="cdktf.Token.asStringMap.parameter.displayHint"></a>

- _Type:_ str
- _Default:_ no display hint

A hint for the Token's purpose when stringifying it.

---

##### `is_unresolved` <a name="is_unresolved" id="cdktf.Token.isUnresolved"></a>

```python
import cdktf

cdktf.Token.is_unresolved(
  obj: typing.Any
)
```

Returns true if obj represents an unresolved value.

One of these must be true:

- `obj` is an IResolvable
- `obj` is a string containing at least one encoded `IResolvable`
- `obj` is either an encoded number or list

This does NOT recurse into lists or objects to see if they
containing resolvables.

###### `obj`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="obj" id="cdktf.Token.isUnresolved.parameter.obj"></a>

- _Type:_ typing.Any

The object to test.

---

##### `null_value` <a name="null_value" id="cdktf.Token.nullValue"></a>

```python
import cdktf

cdktf.Token.null_value()
```

Return a Token containing a `null` value.

Note: This is different than `undefined`, `nil`, `None` or similar
as it will end up in the Terraform config and can be used to explicitly
not set an attribute (which is sometimes required by Terraform providers)

#### Constants <a name="Constants" id="Constants"></a>

| **Name**                                                                                       | **Type**                              | **Description**                        |
| ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------- |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Token.property.ANY_MAP_TOKEN_VALUE">ANY_MAP_TOKEN_VALUE</a></code>       | <code>str</code>                      | Any map token representation.          |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Token.property.NUMBER_MAP_TOKEN_VALUE">NUMBER_MAP_TOKEN_VALUE</a></code> | <code>typing.Union[int, float]</code> | Number Map token value representation. |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.Token.property.STRING_MAP_TOKEN_VALUE">STRING_MAP_TOKEN_VALUE</a></code> | <code>str</code>                      | String Map token value representation. |

---

##### `ANY_MAP_TOKEN_VALUE`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="ANY_MAP_TOKEN_VALUE" id="cdktf.Token.property.ANY_MAP_TOKEN_VALUE"></a>

```python
ANY_MAP_TOKEN_VALUE: str
```

- _Type:_ str

Any map token representation.

---

##### `NUMBER_MAP_TOKEN_VALUE`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="NUMBER_MAP_TOKEN_VALUE" id="cdktf.Token.property.NUMBER_MAP_TOKEN_VALUE"></a>

```python
NUMBER_MAP_TOKEN_VALUE: typing.Union[int, float]
```

- _Type:_ typing.Union[int, float]

Number Map token value representation.

##### `is_resolvable` <a name="is_resolvable" id="cdktf.Tokenization.isResolvable"></a>

```python
import cdktf

cdktf.Tokenization.is_resolvable(
  obj: typing.Any
)
```

Return whether the given object is an IResolvable object.

This is different from Token.isUnresolved() which will also check for
encoded Tokens, whereas this method will only do a type check on the given
object.

###### `obj`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="obj" id="cdktf.Tokenization.isResolvable.parameter.obj"></a>

- _Type:_ typing.Any

---

##### `resolve` <a name="resolve" id="cdktf.Tokenization.resolve"></a>

```python
import cdktf

cdktf.Tokenization.resolve(
  obj: typing.Any,
  resolver: ITokenResolver,
  scope: IConstruct,
  preparing: bool = None
)
```

Resolves an object by evaluating all tokens and removing any undefined or empty objects or arrays.

Values can only be primitives, arrays or tokens. Other objects (i.e. with methods) will be rejected.

###### `obj`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="obj" id="cdktf.Tokenization.resolve.parameter.obj"></a>

- _Type:_ typing.Any

The object to resolve.

---

###### `resolver`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="resolver" id="cdktf.Tokenization.resolve.parameter.resolver"></a>

- _Type:_ <a href="#cdktf.ITokenResolver">ITokenResolver</a>

The resolver to apply to any resolvable tokens found.

---

###### `scope`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="scope" id="cdktf.Tokenization.resolve.parameter.scope"></a>

- _Type:_ constructs.IConstruct

The scope from which resolution is performed.

---

###### `preparing`<sup>Optional</sup> <a name="preparing" id="cdktf.Tokenization.resolve.parameter.preparing"></a>

- _Type:_ bool
- _Default:_ false

Whether the resolution is being executed during the prepare phase or not.

---
